Thanks for joining our live coverage on an extraordinary day in court, with adult-film star Stormy Daniels taking the stand.

It was a tense courtroom, with Daniels warned to dial back her comments at times. Prosecutors were also told to limit their questions regarding the salacious details of her alleged sexual encounter with Trump (which Trump has denied ever took place).

Here's our full wrap of what happened in court today.

This page was edited by Tiffany Wertheimer, Lisa Lambert, Brandon Livesay and Phil McCausland. The writers were Sam Hancock and Sean Seddon, and we had Madeline Halpert and Kayla Epstein in court.

Court doesn't sit on Wednesday, so we'll be back on Thursday, when Stormy Daniels will once again take to the stand to continue her testimony.

On Thursday, Stormy Daniels will be back in court to continue her testimony. This time, she will be questioned about her alleged sexual encounter with Donald Trump. The president has denied the allegations, but Daniels is determined to tell her story.

In the meantime, here's a look at some of the key moments from her testimony so far.

1. Daniels described the moment she met Trump at a celebrity golf tournament in 2006.

"I remember being introduced to him, and him being extremely confident and cocky," Daniels said. "I remember thinking, 'He's a dick.'"

2. Daniels said Trump invited her to his hotel room and that they had sex.

"He was talking about how he wanted me to be on The Apprentice," Daniels said. "And then he just started talking about, you know, how great I would look on TV."

3. Daniels said Trump offered to help her career in exchange for sex.

"He was like, 'Would you do me a favor?'" Daniels said. "And I was like, 'Yeah, what?' And he was like, 'Would you do me a favor and show me your boobs?'"

4. Daniels said Trump made her sign a non-disclosure agreement.

"He made me sign this non-disclosure agreement, and he said that if I ever told anybody about this, I would be sued," Daniels said.

5. Daniels said Trump threatened to sue her if she spoke about the incident.

"He said he would ruin my life if I ever told anybody about what happened," Daniels said.

6. Daniels said she was afraid to speak out about the incident for years.

"I was afraid of him," Daniels said. "I was afraid of what he would do, what he might do."

7. Daniels said she decided to speak out after Trump was elected president.

"I felt like I had to," Daniels said. "I felt like it was my responsibility."

8. Daniels said she is not afraid of Trump anymore.

"I'm not afraid of him anymore," Daniels said. "I'm not afraid of what he can do to me."

9. Daniels said she is telling her story to help other women who have been silenced.

"I want to be an advocate for other women who have been silenced," Daniels said. "I want to be a voice for them."

10. Daniels said she is not doing this for the money.

"I'm not doing this for the money," Daniels said. "I'm doing this because I believe it's the right thing to do."
